Awesome 2025-04-21 02:59 a.m.
In State of Mayflower v. marinesinaction13, No. CR-0094-25, Ruling on Defendant’s Motion to Merge (Mayfl. Dist. Ct. 2025), the court there concluded that Aggravated Battery is a lesser-included offense of First-Degree Murder. Whilst I am, of course, not bound to follow that recent decision, I consider it seriously persuasive and that I ought to give some deference to it (it was also the basis for the Court’s prior decision), given it is the only case that I was able to find (in Mayflower) that is on point. That being said, as you have raised an objection to the Court sua sponte merging Counts 1 and 2, I’ve opted to reconsider whether to apply marinesinaction13. For the reasons that now follow, I conclude that marinesinaction13 was likely incorrectly decided as a matter of law and, thus, that the Court ought to vacate its prior decision to merge Counts 1 & 2.

Elements of Aggravated Battery: (1) A person, (2) who wilfully and maliciously, (3) touches another person, (4) with an object capable of causing severe harm thereto. 1 M.S.C. § 2303.
Elements of First Degree Murder: (1) A person, who intentionally and maliciously, (4) kills another person, (5) with premeditation, (6) or whilst in the commission of a felony, (7) or who is a uniformed or clearly identifiable civil servant in the commission of their duties. 1 M.S.C. § 2101.
Awesome 2025-04-21 02:59 a.m.
First-Degree Murder is indisputably the more serious of the two. “[T]he test to be applied to determine whether there are two offenses or only one is whether each provision requires proof of an additional fact which the other does not.” United States v. Blockburger, 284 U.S. 299, 304 (1932) (citing Gavieres v. United States, 220 U. S. 338, 342 (1911)). 1 M.S.C. § 2303 requires proof of an additional fact not required by 1 M.S.C. § 2101, and is thus not a lesser included offense of 1 M.S.C. § 2101: the willful and malicious touching of another person with an object capable of causing severe harm to that person. First-Degree Murder (1 M.S.C. § 2101) can be committed in-game in one of several ways, namely by: (1) shooting, hitting, or beating a person, with or without an object capable of causing severe harm (such as a knife or fire axe); (2) pushing another person to their death; and (3) using explosives.
Reapers 2025-04-21 07:02 p.m.
Thank you for the reconsideration, your honor

Awesome 2025-04-24 08:56 a.m.
MINUTE ORDER TO SHOW CAUSE

On or about April 16, 2025, Defendant DowntownVancouver sent a message to the Court, purporting to offer the Court “[twenty thousand dollars ($20,000)] to dismiss [his] case,” captioned CR-0097-25; in other words, this matter.

Such conduct is prejudicial to the “administration of justice,” constitutes an attempted fraud upon the Court, Herring v. United States, 424 F.3d 384, 386–87 (3d Cir. 2005) (stating that fraud on the court encompasses “bribery of a judge or jury or fabrication of evidence by counsel.” (emphasis added)); see 11 Charles Alan Wright, Arthur R. Miller & Mary Kay Kane, Federal Practice & Procedure § 2870, at 418 (2d ed. 1995) (“[A] fraud on the court is a narrow concept, limited to "the most egregious conduct involving a corruption of the judicial process itself."), and is thus punishable as criminal contempt. 1 M.S.C. § 1501; see Pendergast v. United States, 317 U.S. 412, 416 (1943) (holding that an act constituting fraud on the court, if a contempt, is punishable as criminal contempt under 28 U.S.C. § 385 (1940), amended by 18 U.S.C. § 401, which is analogous if not identical to 1 M.S.C. § 1501.).

Defendant DowntownVancouver is thus ORDERED to show cause, on or before Friday, April 25, 2025 at 7:30 p.m., 4 months ago, why he should not be held in criminal contempt for his attempted bribery of, and attempted fraud upon, the Court.

DONE AND ORDERED in Chambers at Lander, Mayflower, on April 24, 2025.

/s/ AwesomePIays
Mayflower District Judge

cc: @lynx.ca / @Reapers

Awesome 2025-04-27 12:16 p.m.
MINUTE ORDER APPOINTING GUARDIAN AD LITEM

It appearing to the Court that the Defendant in this matter, DowntownVancouver, is and does not have a duly appointed nor authorized representative and is unable or lacks capacity to defend and represent his own interests, and that the proposed guardian ad litem, JaroCycle, is an attorney in good standing with the Mayflower State Bar and has no interests adverse to the Defendant, IT IS HEREBY:

ORDERED that JaroCycle, be, and he hereby is, appointed as guardian ad litem of the Defendant, DowntownVancouver, absent further order of the Court; and IT IS FURTHER

ORDERED that the guardian ad litem be authorized to advocate for and otherwise represent the best interests of the Defendant in this matter or in any matter sufficiently proximate thereto; and IT IS FURTHER

ORDERED that the Defendant shall relay any proposed message(s) to the Court, including any attachment(s), to the guardian ad litem — or, in any dispute concerning the guardian ad litem, to the Prothonotary’s Office — who shall then relay such to the Court, if deemed appropriate; and IT IS FURTHER

ORDERED that the Defendant shall not directly communicate with — including, without limitation, by sending direct message(s) to — the Court.

DONE AND ORDERED in Chambers at Lander, Mayflower, on April 28, 2025.

/s/ AwesomePIays
Mayflower District Judge

Awesome 2025-05-01 02:57 p.m.
PAPERLESS CONTEMPT ORDER

Defendant DowntownVancouver sent a message to the Court, purporting to offer the Court “[twenty thousand dollars ($20,000)] to dismiss [his] case,” captioned CR-0097-25. Defendant then proceeded to make several disparaging and disgraceful remarks in the immediate presence of the Court and, after several warnings, did not desist. Defendant also misled the Court. Defendant is thus found guilty beyond a reasonable doubt of both direct (8 counts) and indirect criminal contempt (1 count), totaling nine (9) counts, in violation of 1 M.S.C. § 1501, and is ORDERED remanded to the custody of the Sheriff of Clark County, to be imprisoned forthwith at the Clark County Prison Complex for sixty (60) minutes on each count, each count to run consecutively, totaling five hundred and forty (540) minutes.
